<section class="card">
  <h2>About Onions</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Long-runway cool-season crop—bulb size depends on early establishment and seasonal heat.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Onions tolerate light frost once established but require a long development window.</strong>
    For GrowByDate modeling, frost is defined as 32°F (0°C). In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), onion viability depends on starting early enough to build plant size before bulbing begins, then accumulating enough seasonal heat to mature before fall frost.
  </p>

  <p>
    Onions are time-dependent crops. In short seasons, success hinges less on surviving frost and more on securing enough runway between last frost and first frost for bulb formation and curing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Start indoors:</strong> 10–12 weeks before transplant window</li>
    <li><strong>Transplant:</strong> 2–4 weeks before last frost (after hardening off)</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 90–120 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> Light (established plants tolerate brief dips near 32°F / 0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are baseline ranges. Variety type (short-day, intermediate-day, long-day) must match latitude for proper bulbing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Cold Tolerance & Temperature Profile</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 55–75°F (13–24°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below ~40°F (4°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Heat stress:</strong> Above ~85°F (29°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Planning frost boundary:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Onions tolerate light frost once established, making early transplanting feasible in many climates.
    However, hard or repeated freezes can damage foliage and reduce growth rate.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    For frost probability context, see:
    <a href="/guides/average-frost-date-vs-actual-weather/">Average frost date vs actual weather</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Runway & Bulbing Logic</h2>

  <p>
    Onions first build leaf mass, then begin bulbing as day length increases.
    If plants are too small when bulbing begins, final bulb size is limited.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Too late to start:</strong> Reduced bulb size due to limited vegetative growth</li>
    <li><strong>On time:</strong> Adequate leaf growth before bulbing</li>
    <li><strong>Too early:</strong> Risk of transplant stress in extreme cold</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Use the <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Starting Planner</a> to determine indoor start timing from your last frost date.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~1,200–1,800 GDD (base 50) depending on variety and desired bulb size</p>

  <p>
    Onions are moderately heat-dependent. Weak heat accumulation during spring and early summer can slow development and delay maturity.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For the combined frost + heat model, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Most onion varieties require <strong>90–120 frost-free days</strong> from transplant to maturity.
    In short seasons, starting indoors early is critical to preserve enough runway.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Sometimes (early varieties + early indoor starts required)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Often, unless started very early indoors</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Rarely for frost protection, but early indoor starts are essential</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Onions tolerate light frost near 32°F (0°C), but sustained hard freezes can damage foliage.
    For planning, treat 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary and aim to mature bulbs with buffer ahead of fall freeze.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Start seeds indoors 10–12 weeks before transplant window</li>
    <li>Select varieties suited to your latitude (long-day vs short-day)</li>
    <li>Transplant early into cool conditions after hardening off</li>
    <li>Prioritize full sun to maximize effective heat accumulation</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, onion viability depends on securing enough runway before bulbing begins and accumulating sufficient heat before first frost.
    Short frost windows require disciplined indoor starts and appropriate variety selection.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can onions survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Established onions tolerate light frost near 32°F (0°C), though repeated hard freezes can damage foliage.
  </p>

  <h3>Why are my onion bulbs small?</h3>
  <p>
    Most often, plants did not build enough leaf mass before bulbing began, usually due to late starting or insufficient runway.
  </p>

  <h3>Are onions difficult in short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    They can be. Early indoor starts and proper day-length variety selection are essential for reliable bulb sizing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Onions require long runway: 90–120 days, ~1,200–1,800 GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Indoor starts are critical in short seasons.</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>